description: From Latin mēum (“umbelliferous plant, Meum athamanticum”), from Ancient Greek μῆον (mêon), probably from μεῖον (meîon, “lesser”) for its small size. The English form came perhaps via Middle French meu, a word with a single isolated attestation from the 14th century which only began to appear consistently from 1568, by which time the word was established in English.

examples: Synonyms: meon, meum, baldmoney, spignel, bearwort

entries.meaning: (historical) The second minister of the Kingdom of Dahomey.
